# Cron & Crontab Guide (A–Z)

A  guide to **cron** and **crontab** in Linux systems.
This README explains **what cron is, how it works, configuration options, scheduling syntax, environment behavior, and real-world usage**.


# What is Cron

**Cron** is a **time-based job scheduler** in Linux systems.

It allows users to schedule commands or scripts to run automatically at specified times or intervals.

Examples:
- Daily backups
- Log rotation
- Database maintenance
- System monitoring scripts
- Automated deployments

Cron runs as a **daemon service**:


# What is Crontab

**Crontab (Cron Table)** is a file that defines scheduled jobs.

Each user on a Linux system can have their own crontab file containing scheduled tasks.

Cron reads these files and executes the jobs accordingly.


Cron works with several components:

|---- user crontab files
|---- /etc/crontab
|---- /etc/cron.d/
|---- /etc/cron.hourly
|---- /etc/cron.daily
|---- /etc/cron.weekly
|---- /etc/cron.monthly

The **cron daemon** periodically scans these locations and runs jobs when schedules match.



